            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-4">Italy is one of the European countries that attracts the largest number of annual tourists in the world. Italy has long been famous for its romantic works and lyrical beauty. This land is the origin of many long-standing cultures in the world.</p>
            <p class="handbook-title-1 mt-3">Climate of Italy</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Thanks to the latitude-long peninsula and the mostly mountainous terrain in the interior, Italy's climate is highly diverse. In most of the northern and central inland regions, the climate varies from humid subtropical to humid continental and oceanic. In particular, the climate of the Po Valley geographical region is mostly continental, with harsh winters and hot summers.The coastal areas of Liguria, Tuscany and most of the south generally conform to a Mediterranean climate pattern (Köppen climate classification Csa). Conditions in the coastal areas of the peninsula are very different from the inland highlands and valleys, especially during the winter months when higher elevations tend to be cold, wet and often snowy. Coastal areas have mild winters and warm and often dry summers, but lowland valleys can be quite hot in summer. Average winter temperatures range from 0 °C in the Alps to 12 °C in Sicily, while average summer temperatures range from 20 °C to 25 °C.</p>
