            <img src="~/Content/Images/Home/Handbook/Italy/italy-2.jpg" width="100%" />
            <p class="note-img">Subway in Italy</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>Subway</b>: this is a commonly used means of transport in Italy, it is fast and punctual. In Italy, they divide the subway into many types, Accelerato, regionale and locale are slow trains, they stop at all stations. Diretto moves faster, stops at fewer stops, Espresso only runs through main cities.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>Taxi</b>: in Rome city there are many taxis, however there are many taxis operating without a license and the prices are often much more expensive than licensed taxis. You should only choose taxis that are white or yellow in color, and have the SPQR character right at the front door.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>Bus</b>: is a cheap public transportation in Italy. Instead of traveling by taxi, you can save a decent amount of money if you travel by bus.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>Motorbikes, bicycles</b>: if you want freedom of time, you can rent a motorbike to walk around the city. Motorbike prices are quite high, for motorbikes under 125 cc you have to pay up to 50 Euro/day, for bicycles it is about 7.5 Euro/day cheaper.</p>

